      "name": "",
      "username": "Alex",
      "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.trainerday.com/alex/{size}/1331_2.png",
      "created_at": "2024-01-10T08:31:39.503Z",
      "cooked": "<p>I answered this in my possibly confusing answer above.  I will try to say it more clearly.</p>\n<p>Because higher fitness score usually means more duration spent, then there is a correlation between fitness score and cycling performance.  Trying to maximize your fitness score is not a clear way (at least long term) to maximum cycling performance, although it can work but it usually burns you out if you do it too long.</p>\n<p>The word fitness it\u2019s self does not have any clear definition so I will use cycling performance.  Fitness probably includes strength training which is not clearly correlated to cycling performance.</p>\n<p>Chasing maximum fitness score can be fun and motivate you.</p>",
