      "id": 42976,
      "name": "",
      "username": "Alex",
      "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.trainerday.com/alex/{size}/1331_2.png",
      "created_at": "2024-01-10T08:41:19.195Z",
      "cooked": "<p>CTL  (Chronic Training Load) = Fitness score in intervals.  TrainingPeaks owns the terms  TSS/CTL/TSB so intervals does not use them (we don\u2019t either but we could because we are partners with them).  CTL is the more universally recognized term for Fitness Score.  And you can search google for these terms and get more information.</p>\n<p>TSB is Training Stress Balance.  I don\u2019t know what Intervals calls it.  Basically if you go negative for too long with your TSB you are wearing your body down and you get sick, injured, start sleeping poorly.  TSB (like all these numbers) are not totally accurate, meaning some people could be -30 for a few days and have issues another others might be able to sustain -30 for 10 days for example.  If you are really trying to maximize your \u201cfitness\u201d or CTL, you need to find your own limits for TSB.</p>\n<p>So when you increase your weekly average TSS too quickly, then your TSB gets out of whack (goes too negative). \u201cToo much, too soon.\u201d  Meaning you are taking risks.  Too much intensity too soon usually has more risk than too much duration too soon, but both have risks.</p>",
